**Full citation:** L. C. Berselli and H. Beir√£o da Veiga, "On the regularizing effect of the vorticity direction in incompressible viscous flows," *Differential and Integral Equations*, 15(3), 345‚Äì356 (2002).

**Exact theorem statement:** Let Œ≤ ‚àà (0,1]. If the vorticity direction Œæ = œâ/|œâ| satisfies Œ≤-H√∂lder continuity |Œæ(x,t) ‚àí Œæ(y,t)| ‚â§ K|x ‚àí y|^Œ≤ in the high-vorticity region {|œâ| ‚â• M}, then regularity holds provided Œ≤ ‚â• 1/2. The exponent Œ≤ = 1/2 is the critical threshold.

**What makes it an improvement:** Weakens the Constantin-Fefferman hypothesis from Lipschitz (Œ≤ = 1) to ¬Ω-H√∂lder (Œ≤ = 1/2). The condition is strictly weaker ‚Äî no regularity claim was made at Œ≤ = 1/2 before this paper.

**Key assumption:** Œ≤-H√∂lder coherence with Œ≤ ‚â• 1/2. The constant K need not be small.

**Quantitative or qualitative:** Qualitative.

**Addresses Ladyzhenskaya bottleneck?** No ‚Äî same orthogonal mechanism.

